      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism is fundamentally rooted in the idea that the Constitution is a fixed document, not a living thing that can be constantly reinterpreted by judges. Its core logic is that the framers intended a specific meaning for the text at the time it was adopted, and judges must adhere to that original public understanding. This approach prevents unelected judges from imposing their own modern policy preferences onto the law. Therefore, originalism ensures judicial restraint and fidelity to the founders' intent.",
